-- Persian Gulf Stocks: Al-Mojil, Tabuk Cement, Tamweel, Zoujaj
-- B y   Z a h r a   H a n k i r
-- 2012-04-16T12:52:49Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-04-16/persian-gulf-stocks-commercial-facilities-doha-insurance-gain.html
The  DFM General Index (DFMGI)  fell 1.6
percent, the most since March 29, to 1,649.25 at the 2 p.m.
close in Dubai.  Abu Dhabi ’s  ADX General Index (ADSMI)  declined 0.5
percent and  Saudi Arabia ’s  Tadawul All Share Index (SASEIDX)  retreated 1
percent.  The following shares were active in the Persian Gulf
region. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Qatar International Islamic Bank (QIIK)   fell the most
since March 7, losing 1.2 percent to 50.9 riyals. The company
may sell Islamic bonds this year, the chief executive officer
said.  Mohammad Al-Mojil Group Co. (MMG)   advanced 2 percent,
the biggest gain in a week, to 15.05 riyals. The Saudi Arabian
construction services provider said its board decided to hire a
bank to advise on restructuring its debt.  National Company for Glass Industries  (ZOUJAJ AB) fell 2.6
percent, the most since April 10, to 37.6 riyals. The Saudi
maker of bottles and jars known as Zoujaj said first-quarter
profit fell 29 percent to 17.7 million riyals ($4.7 million).  Tabuk Cement Co. (TACCO)   gained the most since March 25,
rising 1.6 percent to 25.5 riyals. The manufacturer of the
building material said first-quarter profit rose to 49.2 million
riyals from 41.2 million riyals a year earlier.  Tamweel PJSC (TAMWEEL)   declined the most in a week,
falling 2.8 percent to 1.39 dirhams. The United Arab Emirates
mortgage lender said it may consider tapping the  debt market 
again this year after raising $300 million from the sale of
Islamic bonds in January.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Zahra Hankir in Dubai at 
 zhankir@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
